From the perspective of A, the only important thing is that B returns a Task. It doesn't care whether B uses async/await or not.

The line  
var resultset = await rep.B(input1, input2);  
is the same as  
var bTask = rep.B(input1, input2);  
var resultset = await bTask;

In other words, A calls B directly (synchronously). B will (presumably) return an incomplete task. A then awaits on that task, which causes A to return an incomplete task.

Note that at this point both B and A have returned incomplete tasks, but they are not finished executing yet.

When B completes, it will complete the task it previously returned to A. This will cause A to resume executing, and when it completes, it will complete the task it previously returned to its caller.

